


     PPPPIIIIPPPPEEEESSSS((((UUUU1111))))            LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111             PPPPIIIIPPPPEEEESSSS((((UUUU1111))))



     NNNNaaaammmmeeee
          PIPES - Executes one or more commands from a single command
          line.

     SSSSyyyynnnnttttaaaaxxxx
          ppppiiiippppeeeessss [ ----ssssnnnnrrrreeee????hhhh ] [ ----dddd _d_r_i_v_e_n_u_m_b_e_r ] _p_r_o_g_r_a_m #_1
          [ |||| _p_r_o_g_r_a_m #_2 ] ...  [ |||| _p_r_o_g_r_a_m #_n ] [< _f_i_l_e | _d_e_v_i_c_e ]
          [>[>] _f_i_l_e | _d_e_v_i_c_e ] [ ; _n_e_x_t _c_o_m_m_a_n_d _g_r_o_u_p ]

     DDDDeeeessssccccrrrriiiippppttttiiiioooonnnn
          _P_i_p_e_s executes one or more commands or programs from a
          single command line.  Each command to be executed is
          separated by a semicolon (';;;;') or a pipe ('||||').  Separating
          commands with semicolons allows you to specify several LS-
          DOS commands or program names using a single command line.

          When the ppppiiiippppeeee operator ('||||') is used instead of a semicolon,
          the text from one program that would normally be displayed
          is stored on disk and is provided as input to the next
          program that is specified.  The output of the second program
          can then be "piped" to a third program, and so on.  For
          example, if you would like to search through a directory
          display using the standard LS-DOS _d_i_r(L) command, you can
          use a command like:    ppppiiiippppeeeessss ddddiiiirrrr ::::0000 ((((nnnn)))) |||| mmmmoooorrrreeee
          In this example, the output of the LS-DOS library command
          _d_i_r(_L) is intercepted and written to a file instead of being
          displayed, as originally programmed.  Then the second
          program, the _m_o_r_e(U1) program, is run and when it reads from
          what it thinks is the keyboard, it is actually reading the
          data from _d_i_r(L) that has been stored in a file.  Because
          _m_o_r_e(U1) is the last program is this "pipeline", its output
          goes to the display.

          Pipes are a powerful technique that allows compound programs
          to be created.  This is done by connecting smaller programs
          together.  These programs are unaware of the other programs
          they are passing data to and from, and this means that many
          existing programs and commands can be used without having to
          modify them.

          The idea for _p_i_p_e_s comes from the *NIX operating system, and
          is a standard feature in all versions.  In the *NIX
          implementation, each program specified on the command line
          is run simultaneously, so as soon as the first program
          produces data, the second program can read it.  Since LS-DOS
          is not a multi-tasking operating system, each program must
          run entirely before the next program can be started and
          allowed to see the data from the first program.  This
          creates a few restrictions in how _p_i_p_e_s can be used, but
          these are minor.





     Page 1                                             May 15th, 1993






     PPPPIIIIPPPPEEEESSSS((((UUUU1111))))            LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111             PPPPIIIIPPPPEEEESSSS((((UUUU1111))))



          _P_i_p_e_s accepts several options.  Options are usually
          specified by single characters, and they may be entered in
          upper or lowercase.  Options are always preceded by a hyphen
          (a "-").  If you are specifying multiple options, you can
          specify the options in any of these formats:
                -a -b -c   or   -abc   or   -a -bc   or  -ab -c

          The options are:

          ----dddd _d_r_i_v_e_n_u_m_b_e_r
               Specifies what logical drive _p_i_p_e_s should use for the
               temporary files it creates.

          ----ssss   When the first program attempts to read from the
               keyboard (the *KI device), ppppiiiippppeeeessss will provide a <SPACE>
               (ASCII 0x20) character to the program instead of
               actually letting it read the keyboard.  No matter how
               many times the program tries to read the keyboard, it
               will always receive a <SPACE> character instead.  This
               option is useful if the program being executed pauses
               the display and is simply looking for a character to
               allow it continue.  By default, the LS-DOS command
               _d_i_r(L) does this.

          ----nnnn   Same as ----ssss, except a <NULL> (ASCII 0x00) is supplied to
               the program.

          ----rrrr   Same as ----ssss, except a <ENTER> (ASCII 0x0D) is supplied
               to the program.

          ----eeee   Similar to ----ssss, except that when the program tries to
               read the keyboard, it will always receive an end-of-
               file error (ASCII 0x1C).  Some programs will exit when
               they see an EOF, and this may be desirable.

          ----???? or ----hhhh
               Displays the help message.

          <<<< _f_i_l_e | _d_e_v_i_c_e
               If a file or device is specified, when the first
               program specified tries to read data from the keyboard,
               _p_i_p_e_s will provide data from the file or device until
               the end-of-file is detected or an error occurs.  This
               is known as _r_e_d_i_r_e_c_t_e_d _i_n_p_u_t. _F_i_l_e_s_p_e_c_s for redirection
               may not specify a password.










     Page 2                                             May 15th, 1993






     PPPPIIIIPPPPEEEESSSS((((UUUU1111))))            LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111             PPPPIIIIPPPPEEEESSSS((((UUUU1111))))



          >>>>[>>>>] _f_i_l_e | _d_e_v_i_c_e
               By specifying a file or device, the output of the last
               program before the end of the line or before a
               semicolon (';;;;') is sent to the specified file or device
               instead of the display.  This is known as _r_e_d_i_r_e_c_t_e_d
               _o_u_t_p_u_t. For example, the command ppppiiiippppeeeessss lllliiiibbbb >>>> lllliiiibbbbtttteeeexxxxtttt::::0000
               places the text from the _l_i_b(L) command in the file
               LLLLIIIIBBBBTTTTEEEEXXXXTTTT::::0000.  If >> is used, the output will be appended
               to any existing contents of the file.  _F_i_l_e_s_p_e_c_s for
               redirection may not specify a password.

          |||| _p_r_o_g_r_a_m
               The pipe symbol ('||||') indicates the end of one program
               specification, and the start of the next.  Unlike the
               semicolon symbol (';;;;'), the pipe symbol ('||||') instructs
               _p_i_p_e_s to store all of the output of the program on the
               left of the pipe symbol, and provide that data to the
               program on the right of the pipe symbol.  On the Model
               4, 4D or 4P keyboard, the pipe symbol is produced by
               holding down the <CLEAR> key, then hold down the
               <SHIFT> key, then press the </> key.

          ;;;; _n_e_x_t _c_o_m_m_a_n_d _g_r_o_u_p
               When _p_i_p_e_s encounters a semicolon (';;;;'), all options
               and redirection resets.  Then the remaining command
               line is examined for new options, program names, pipes,
               and any new redirection specifications.  A single
               command line for _p_i_p_e_s can have as many semicolon-
               separated commands as desired.


     NNNNooootttteeeessss
          Pipes works by loading a driver into high memory that
          intercepts I/O to the *DO, *SI, and the *KI devices.  _P_i_p_e_s
          also intercepts the @EXIT and @ABORT supervisor calls.  When
          _p_i_p_e_s is invoked, it examines the command line up to the
          first semicolon it finds, looking for any redirection
          specifications.  Then it goes back to the start of the
          command line looking for any options.  When a program
          specification is found, that program is executed with the
          input and output routed as specified. Here are some examples
          of how _p_i_p_e_s interprets different command lines:

                ppppiiiippppeeeessss pppprrrrooooggggrrrraaaammmm1111 <<<< ffffiiiilllleeeeaaaa >>>> ffffiiiilllleeeebbbb

          PPPPRRRROOOOGGGGRRRRAAAAMMMM1111 is executed.  If PPPPRRRROOOOGGGGRRRRAAAAMMMM1111 tries to read data from
          the keyboard, the data is actually read from FFFFIIIILLLLEEEEAAAA.
          Anything that PPPPRRRROOOOGGGGRRRRAAAAMMMM1111 wants to display is stored in FFFFIIIILLLLEEEEBBBB.
          Note that the <<<< and >>>> specifications, plus any other
          parameters that are used by _p_i_p_e_s are not passed to the
          programs being executed.




     Page 3                                             May 15th, 1993






     PPPPIIIIPPPPEEEESSSS((((UUUU1111))))            LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111             PPPPIIIIPPPPEEEESSSS((((UUUU1111))))



                ppppiiiippppeeeessss ----ssss pppprrrrooooggggrrrraaaammmm1111 >>>> ffffiiiilllleeeeaaaa

          PPPPRRRROOOOGGGGRRRRAAAAMMMM1111 is executed.  If PPPPRRRROOOOGGGGRRRRAAAAMMMM1111 tries to read a character
          from the keyboard, it will always get a <SPACE> character.
          Any output from PPPPRRRROOOOGGGGRRRRAAAAMMMM1111 is stored in FFFFIIIILLLLEEEEAAAA.

                ppppiiiippppeeeessss ddddaaaatttteeee ;;;; ddddeeeevvvviiiicccceeee ((((bbbb====yyyyeeeessss)))) >>>> ffffiiiilllleeeeaaaa ;;;; lllliiiibbbb

          The programs _d_a_t_e(L), _d_e_v_i_c_e(L) and _l_i_b(L) are executed in
          that order.  The output of _d_a_t_e(L) and _l_i_b(L) goes to the
          display since they are not redirected.  The output of
          _d_e_v_i_c_e(L) is stored in FFFFIIIILLLLEEEEAAAA.  The parameter to the
          _d_e_v_i_c_e(L) program is passed just as it was present on a
          normal LS-DOS command line.

                ppppiiiippppeeeessss ddddaaaatttteeee >>>> ffffiiiilllleeeeaaaa ;;;; ttttiiiimmmmeeee >>>>>>>> ffffiiiilllleeeeaaaa

          The programs _d_a_t_e(L) and _t_i_m_e(L) are executed in that order.
          The output of _d_a_t_e(L) is stored in the file FFFFIIIILLLLEEEEAAAA, and the
          output of _t_i_m_e(L) is appended to the contents of FFFFIIIILLLLEEEEAAAA.

                ppppiiiippppeeeessss lllliiiibbbb |||| wwwwcccc

          The library command lib(L) is executed and the display
          output is stored on disk.  Then the program _w_c(U1) is
          executed and reads the data from _l_i_b(L) that was stored.
          Since _w_c is at the end of the pipeline and there is no
          redirection, its output is sent to the display.
          Note that the spaces around the |||| and ;;;; in these examples
          are optional.  The command ppppiiiippppeeeessss lllliiiibbbb||||wwwwcccc is accepted.

                ppppiiiippppeeeessss ttttiiiimmmmeeee ;;;; wwwwcccc |||| mmmmoooorrrreeee ++++////1111 <<<< ffffiiiilllleeeeaaaa >>>> ffffiiiilllleeeebbbb ;;;; ddddaaaatttteeee

          The library command _t_i_m_e(L) is executed and its output is
          sent to the display.  Then the program _w_c(U1) is executed
          and it reads data from FFFFIIIILLLLEEEEAAAA.  The output of _w_c(U1) is
          stored on disk.  Then the program _m_o_r_e(U1) is executed and
          it reads the data from _w_c(U1) that was stored on disk.  The
          output of _m_o_r_e(U1) is stored in FFFFIIIILLLLEEEEBBBB.  Finally, the _d_a_t_e(L)
          command is executed and its output is displayed.















